{"title_page": "Oh, Pretty Woman", "text_new": "{{about||the film named after this song|Pretty Woman|the musical named after this song|Pretty Woman: The Musical|the other song of the same name by Gary Moore|Still Got the Blues}}\n{{short description|American single}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name          = Oh, Pretty Woman \n| cover         = Ohprettywoman.jpg\n| cover_size    = \n| alt           = \n| border        = \n| caption       = Side A of 1964 US single\n| type          = single\n| artist        = [[Roy Orbison]] and [[the Candymen|the Candy Men]]\n| album         = \n| B-side        = Yo te Amo Mar\u00eda\n| released      = August 28, 1964<ref>http://www.45cat.com/record/45851</ref>\n| format        = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded      = August 1, 1964\n| studio        = \n| genre         = [[Rock and roll]]\n| length        = {{Duration|m=2|s=55}}\n| label         = [[Monument Records|Monument]]\n| writer        = \n*Roy Orbison\n*[[Bill Dees]]\n| producer      = [[Fred Foster]]\n| prev_title    = [[It's Over (Roy Orbison song)|It's Over]]\n| prev_year     = 1964\n| next_title    = Goodnight\n| next_year     = 1965\n| misc          = {{Audio sample\n | type = single\n | file = Roy Orbison - Oh, Pretty Woman.ogg\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Oh, Pretty Woman'''\" or \"'''Pretty Woman'''\" is a beeka song recorded by [[Roy Orbison]], written by Orbison and [[Bill Dees]].<ref name=\"500 Number One Hits\">{{cite book| first= Jo| last= Rice|year= 1982| title= The Guinness Book of 500 Number One Hits| edition= 1st| publisher= Guinness Superlatives Ltd | location= Enfield, Middlesex| page= 85| isbn= 0-85112-250-7}}</ref> It was released as a single in August 1964 on [[Monument Records]] and spent three weeks at number one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] from September 26, 1964, the second single by Orbison to top the US charts.<ref>[[Fred Bronson|Bronson, Fred]] (2003). ''The Billboard Book of #1 Hits'', 5th Edition (Billboard Publications), page 157.</ref> It was also Orbison's third single to top the [[UK Singles Chart]] (for a total of three weeks).<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book| first= David| last= Roberts| year= 2006| title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]| edition= 19th| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited | location= London| isbn= 1-904994-10-5| page= 186}}</ref> The record ultimately sold seven million copies and marked the high point in Orbison's career.<ref>Lehman, Peter. ''Roy Orbison: Invention of an Alternative Rock Masculinity''. Philadelphia: Temple UP, 2003, p. 2, 13</ref> Within months of its release, in October 1964, the single was certified [[gold record|gold]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]].<ref>{{cite certification|region=United States|title=Pretty Woman|artist=Roy Orbison}}</ref> At the year's end, ''Billboard'' ranked it the number four song of 1964.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=January 2, 1965|title=Hot 100 Singles of 1964|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/60s/1965/Billboard%201965-01-02.pdf|journal=Billboard|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> \"Oh, Pretty Woman\" was eventually the basis for the 1990 film ''[[Pretty Woman]]'' starring [[Richard Gere]] and [[Julia Roberts]], and the 2018 Broadway musical ''[[Pretty Woman: The Musical]]''.\n\n==Overview==\nThe lyrics tell the story of a man who sees a pretty woman walking by. He yearns for her and wonders if, as beautiful as she is, she might be lonely like he is. At the last minute, she turns back and joins him. The title was inspired by Orbison's wife, Claudette, interrupting a conversation to announce she was going out. When Orbison asked if she had enough cash, his co-writer Bill Dees interjected, \"[[Roy Orbison#Riding the success|A pretty woman never needs any money]].\"<ref>Amburn, Ellis. ''Dark Star: The Roy Orbison Story''. New York: Carol Publishing, 1990, p. 127</ref>\n\nOrbison's recording of the song was produced by [[Fred Foster]]<ref name=\"500 Number One Hits\" /> on 1 August 1964. There were four guitar players on the session: Roy Orbison, Billy Sanford, [[Jerry Kennedy]], and [[Wayne Moss]].<ref name=SessionReport>{{citation |date=7 September 1964 |title=Phonograph Recording Contract, Local Union No. 257 |publisher=American Federation of Musicians of the United States and Canada |publication-place=Fred Foster Sound Studios, Nashville, TN}}</ref> Sanford, who later played on sessions for [[Elvis Presley]], [[Don Williams]] and many others, played the intro guitar.  Williams introduced him as a kid who had just arrived in Nashville, with a borrowed guitar, who heard Orbison was minus a guitar player, went over and got the gig. Other musicians on the record included [[Floyd Cramer]] on piano, [[Henry Strzelecki]] on upright bass, [[Boots Randolph]] and [[Charlie McCoy]] on saxophones, [[Buddy Harman]] on drums, and Paul Garrison on percussion.<ref name=SessionReport /> Orbison played a 12-string [[Epiphone]]. [[Bill Porter (sound engineer)|Bill Porter]] served as recording engineer for the song.<ref>{{Cite AV media notes |title= The Monument Story|title-link= |others= Various|year= |chapter= |url= |access-date= |first= |last= |author-link= |first2= |last2= |author-link2= |page= |pages= |type= |publisher= Sony Music Entertainment|id= A2K66106|location= New York, New York|ref=}}</ref>\n\nOrbison posthumously won the 1991 [[Grammy Award for Best Male Pop Vocal Performance]] for his live recording of \"Oh Pretty Woman\" on his [[HBO]] television special ''[[Roy Orbison and Friends, A Black and White Night]]''. In 1999, the song was honored with a [[Grammy Hall of Fame Award]] and was named one of the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]'s [[The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame's 500 Songs that Shaped Rock and Roll|500 Songs that Shaped Rock and Roll]]. In 2004, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine ranked it #224 on their list of the \"[[500 Greatest Songs of All Time]].\" On May 14, 2008, The [[Library of Congress]] selected the song for preservation in the [[National Recording Registry]].\n\n===Lawsuit against 2 Live Crew===\n{{Further|Campbell v. Acuff-Rose Music, Inc.}}\nIn 1989, rap group [[2 Live Crew]] recorded a [[parody]] of the Orbison song, using the alternate title \"Pretty Woman\", for their album ''[[As Nasty As They Wanna Be#As Clean As They Wanna Be|As Clean As They Wanna Be]]''. 2 Live Crew [[sampling (music)|sample]]d the distinctive [[bassline]] from the Orbison song, but replaced the original lyrics with talk about a hairy woman and her bald-headed friend and their appeal to the singer, as well as denunciation of a \"two-timing woman.\"\n\nOrbison's publisher, [[Acuff-Rose Music]] sued 2 Live Crew on the basis that the [[fair use]] doctrine did not permit reuse of their [[copyright]]ed material for profit. The case, ''[[Campbell v. Acuff-Rose Music, Inc.]]'' went all the way to the [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]]. The Supreme Court decided in 2 Live Crew's favor, greatly expanding the doctrine of fair use and extending its protections to parodies created for profit. It is considered a seminal fair use decision.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Jackson|first1=Matt|title=Commerce versus art: The transformation of fair use|journal=Journal of Broadcasting & Electronic Media|date=March 1995|volume=39|issue=2|pages=190\u2013199|doi=10.1080/08838159509364298}}</ref>\n\n==Chart history==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Chart (1964\u201365)\n! scope=\"col\" | Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite book | title=[[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book (1940\u20131969)]] | author=Kent, David | authorlink=David Kent (historian) | publisher=Australian Chart Book | location=[[Turramurra]] | year=2005 | isbn=0-646-44439-5}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|Austria|5|artist=Roy Orbison|song=Oh, Pretty Woman|accessdate=August 21, 2014}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|Flanders|1|artist=Roy Orbison|song=Oh, Pretty Woman|accessdate=August 21, 2014}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Belgium ([[Ultratop|Ultratop 40]] Wallonia)<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=OSAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA19#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Hits of the World | journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | issue=50 | page=19 | volume=76 | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | date=December 12, 1964 | issn=0006-2510}}</ref>\n| 5\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Canada ([[RPM (magazine)|''RPM'']])<ref name=\"CAN-sin\">{{cite web | url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.4702&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=bb0e7somh8osmahbvuk8ubb1u5 | title=Top Singles \u2013 Volume 2, No. 5, September 28 1964 | publisher=[[Walt Grealis]] | work=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]] | accessdate=August 22, 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313204743/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.4702&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=bb0e7somh8osmahbvuk8ubb1u5 | archive-date=March 13, 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Denmark ([[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry|IFPI]])<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=biAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA15#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Hits of the World | journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | issue=49 | page=15 | volume=76 | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | date=December 5, 1964 | issn=0006-2510}}</ref>\n| 3\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | France ([[Institut fran\u00e7ais d'opinion publique|IFOP]])<ref name=\"FRA-sin\">{{cite web | url=http://www.infodisc.fr/Bilan_O.php | title=Acc\u00e8s direct \u00e0 ces Artistes: Roy Orbison | publisher=InfoDisc | accessdate=August 21, 2014 | language=French | format=select \"Roy ORBISON\" and then click \"Go\" | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140924114622/http://www.infodisc.fr/Bilan_O.php | archivedate=September 24, 2014 }}</ref>\n| 8\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Finland ([[The Official Finnish Charts|Suomen virallinen lista]])<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KEUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA19#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Hits of the World | journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | issue=1 | page=19 | volume=77 | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | date=January 2, 1965 | issn=0006-2510}}</ref>\n| 9\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ireland ([[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA]])<ref name=\"IRL-sin\">{{cite web | url=http://irishcharts.ie/search/placement | title=Search the Charts | publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]] | work=irishcharts.ie | accessdate=August 22, 2014 | format=enter \"Roy Orbison\" into the \"Search by Artist\" box, then select \"Search\" | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721125210/http://irishcharts.ie/search/placement | archive-date=July 21, 2011 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|Dutch40|3|artist=Roy Orbison|song=Pretty Woman|week=1|year=1965|accessdate=August 21, 2014}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|Dutch100|1|artist=Roy Orbison|song=Oh, Pretty Woman|accessdate=August 21, 2014}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|Norway|1|artist=Roy Orbison|song=Oh, Pretty Woman|accessdate=August 21, 2014}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | New Zealand (Lever Hit Parade)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=Lever+hit+parades&qyear=1964&qmonth=Oct&qweek=22-Oct-1964#n_view_location|title=flavour of new zealand - Lever hit parades|author=|date=|website=www.flavourofnz.co.nz|accessdate=April 10, 2018}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Switzerland ([[Swiss Hitparade|Schweizer Hitparade]])<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=mCgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA24#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Hits of the World | journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | issue=8 | page=24 | volume=77 | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | date=February 20, 1965 | issn=0006-2510}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|UK|1|artist=Roy Orbison|song=Oh Pretty Woman|date=1964-10-10|accessdate=August 21, 2014}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|Billboardhot100|1|artist=Roy Orbison|song=Oh, Pretty Woman|artistid={{BillboardID|Roy Orbison}} | accessdate=August 21, 2014}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|West Germany|1|artist=Roy Orbison|song=Oh, Pretty Woman|songid=8630|year=1964|accessdate=May 28, 2019}}\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Chart (1964) !! Rank\n|-\n|South Africa <ref>{{cite web|title=Top 20 Hit Singles of 1964|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/sahits_1964.html|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|15\n|-\n|UK <ref name=\"officialcharts1952\">{{cite web|first= Dan |last= Lane |title= The biggest selling singles of every year revealed! (1952\u20132011) |publisher= [[Official Charts Company]] |date= 18 November 2012 |accessdate= 28 August 2014 |url= http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-biggest-selling-singles-of-every-year-revealed-1952-2011-1720/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= The 100 best-selling singles of 1964 [in the U.K.] |publisher= www.sixtiescity.net |accessdate= 21 February 2018|url= http://www.sixtiescity.net/charts/64chart.htm#top100}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|-\n|US [[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1964|Top Pop Singles (''Billboard'')]]<ref>http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1964.htm</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Sales and certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Canada|type=single|artist=Roy Orbison|title=Oh, Pretty Woman|nocert=yes|salesamount=180,000|salesref=<ref name=goldendiscs>{{cite book|title=The Book of Golden Discs|url=https://archive.org/details/bookofgoldendisc00murr |url-access=registration|quote=three weeks simultaneously.|edition=2, illustrated|first=Joseph|last=Murrells|publisher=[[Barrie & Jenkins]]|isbn=0-214-20480-4|year=1978|access-date=August 21, 2014}}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Germany|type=single|artist=Roy Orbison|title=Oh, Pretty Woman|nocert=yes|salesamount=350,000|salesref=<ref name=goldendiscs/>}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|type=single|artist=Roy Orbison|title=Oh, Pretty Woman|nocert=yes|salesamount=680,000|salesref=<ref name=goldendiscs/>}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|type=single|artist=Roy Orbison|title=Oh, Pretty Woman|award=Gold|certyear=1964|access-date=August 21, 2014}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=true}}\n\n==Van Halen version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name          = (Oh) Pretty Woman\n| cover         = (Oh)_Pretty_Woman_-_Van_Halen.jpg\n| cover_size    = \n| alt           = \n| border        = \n| caption       = \n| type          = single\n| artist        = [[Van Halen]]\n| album         = [[Diver Down]]\n| B-side        = [[Happy Trails (song)|Happy Trails]]\n| released      = {{Start date|1982|02}}\n| format        = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded      = January 1982\n| studio        = [[Sunset Sound]], Los Angeles\n| genre         = [[Hard rock]]\n| length        = {{Duration|m=2|s=55}}\n| label         = [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n| writer        = \n*[[Roy Orbison]]\n*[[Bill Dees]]\n| producer      = [[Ted Templeman]]\n| prev_title    = [[Unchained (song)|Unchained]]\n| prev_year     = 1981\n| next_title    = [[Dancing in the Street#Van Halen version|Dancing in the Street]]\n| next_year     = 1982\n}}\n[[Van Halen]] covered the song on their 1982 album, ''[[Diver Down]]''. It was preceded by a synth-driven intro titled \"Intruder\". For the video of the single, the two songs were joined, giving a running-time of 4:34. This was done to lengthen the song in order to fit the video's running time.\n\nIn the [[music video]], the band members dress as a samurai (bassist [[Michael Anthony (musician)|Michael Anthony]]), Tarzan (drummer [[Alex Van Halen]]), a cowboy (guitarist [[Eddie Van Halen]]), and [[Napoleon]] (frontman [[David Lee Roth]]). Per a hunchbacked onlooker's request, they rescue a captive girl (played by transgender entertainer [[International Chrysis]]). It was one of the first videos banned by [[MTV]], due to its opening sequence, where the captive girl is tied up and fondled against her will by a pair of little people. The ban was eventually lifted, as MTV sister network [[VH1 Classic]] would later air the video.<ref>{{cite web|author=Chad Childers |url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/van-halen-oh-pretty-woman-banned-music-videos/ |title=Van Halen, \u2018Oh Pretty Woman\u2019 \u2013 Banned Music Videos |publisher=Ultimate Classic Rock |accessdate=March 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThis was the band's second Top 20 hit, peaking at #12 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100,<ref>[[Joel Whitburn|Whitburn, Joel]] (2004). ''The Billboard Book of Top 40 Hits'', 8th Edition (Billboard Publications), page 656.</ref> and also peaking at #1 on the ''Billboard'' [[List of Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one songs of the 1980s#1982|Mainstream Rock]] chart.\n\n===Track listing===\n{{track listing\n| headline        = Side A\n| title1          = (Oh) Pretty Woman\n| note1           = Roy Orbison cover\n| writer1         = Orbison, Dees\n| length1         = 2:55\n}}\n{{track listing\n| headline        = Side B\n| title1          = [[Happy Trails (song)|Happy Trails]]\n| note1           = [[Roy Rogers]] cover\n| writer1         = [[Dale Evans]]\n| length1         = 1:03\n}}\n\n===Chart history===\n{{col-begin|width=67%}}\n{{col-2}}\n====Weekly charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1982)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|59\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles<ref>{{cite web|url=|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date= |accessdate=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|15\n|-\n|Netherlands \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|33\n|-\n|[[UK Singles Chart|UK]] <ref>{{cite web|url= |title=Official Charts Company |website=Officialcharts.com |date= |accessdate=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|47\n|-\n|US ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955\u20131990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|12\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' [[Mainstream Rock]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|US [[Cash Box (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] Top 100<ref>[http://cashboxmagazine.com/archives/80s_files/19820424.html Cash Box Top 100 Singles, April 24, 1982]</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|10\n|-\n|}\n\n{{col-2}}\n====Year-end charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Chart (1982) !! Rank\n|-\n|Canada <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.6167&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=mhe12pta2k83e08udtq66ot062|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada|work=collectionscanada.gc.ca|access-date=2020-03-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160811145442/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.6167&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=mhe12pta2k83e08udtq66ot062|archive-date=2016-08-11|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|51\n|-\n|US [[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1982|Top Pop Singles (''Billboard'')]]<ref>{{cite journal |date=December 25, 1982 |title=Talent in Action : Top Pop Singles |page=TIA-20 |journal=Billboard |volume=94 |issue=51 }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|88\n|-\n|US ''Cash Box'' <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/80s_files/1982YESP.html |title=Cash Box Year-End Charts: Top 100 Pop Singles, December 25, 1982 |access-date=March 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331053901/https://tropicalglen.com/Archives/80s_files/1982YESP.html |archive-date=March 31, 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|66\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n===See also===\n*[[List of Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one songs of the 1980s]]\n\n==Hindi version==\nThe Indian musical trio [[Shankar\u2013Ehsaan\u2013Loy]] composed the [[Hindi]] song \"Pretty Woman\", which samples \"Oh, Pretty Woman\", for the [[Bollywood]] film ''[[Kal Ho Naa Ho]]'' (2003).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-roy-would-have-loved-the-bhangra-version-1012304|title=\u2018Roy would have loved the bhangra version\u2019|last=Upadhyay|first=Karishma|date=February 10, 2006|work=[[Daily News and Analysis]]|access-date=September 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|roy-orbison|oh-pretty-woman}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Roy Orbison}}\n{{Van Halen}}\n\n[[Category:1964 songs]]\n[[Category:1964 singles]]\n[[Category:1976 singles]]\n[[Category:1982 singles]]\n[[Category:Roy Orbison songs]]\n[[Category:Van Halen songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Roy Orbison]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Bill Dees]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Fred Foster]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one singles]]\n[[Category:UK Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:RPM Top Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Germany]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Norway]]\n[[Category:Irish Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Grammy Hall of Fame Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Best Male Pop Vocal Performance]]\n[[Category:United States National Recording Registry recordings]]\n[[Category:Monument Records singles]]\n[[Category:Warner Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs about beauty]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the film named after this song|Pretty Woman|the musical named after this song|Pretty Woman: The Musical|the other song of the same name by Gary Moore|Still Got the Blues}}\n{{short description|American single}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name          = Oh, Pretty Woman \n| cover         = Ohprettywoman.jpg\n| cover_size    = \n| alt           = \n| border        = \n| caption       = Side A of 1964 US single\n| type          = single\n| artist        = [[Roy Orbison]] and [[the Candymen|the Candy Men]]\n| album         = \n| B-side        = Yo te Amo Mar\u00eda\n| released      = August 28, 1964<ref>http://www.45cat.com/record/45851</ref>\n| format        = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded      = August 1, 1964\n| studio        = \n| genre         = [[Rock and roll]]\n| length        = {{Duration|m=2|s=55}}\n| label         = [[Monument Records|Monument]]\n| writer        = \n*Roy Orbison\n*[[Bill Dees]]\n| producer      = [[Fred Foster]]\n| prev_title    = [[It's Over (Roy Orbison song)|It's Over]]\n| prev_year     = 1964\n| next_title    = Goodnight\n| next_year     = 1965\n| misc          = {{Audio sample\n | type = single\n | file = Roy Orbison - Oh, Pretty Woman.ogg\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Oh, Pretty Woman'''\" or \"'''Pretty Woman'''\" is a song recorded by [[Roy Orbison]], written by Orbison and [[Bill Dees]].<ref name=\"500 Number One Hits\">{{cite book| first= Jo| last= Rice|year= 1982| title= The Guinness Book of 500 Number One Hits| edition= 1st| publisher= Guinness Superlatives Ltd | location= Enfield, Middlesex| page= 85| isbn= 0-85112-250-7}}</ref> It was released as a single in August 1964 on [[Monument Records]] and spent three weeks at number one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] from September 26, 1964, the second single by Orbison to top the US charts.<ref>[[Fred Bronson|Bronson, Fred]] (2003). ''The Billboard Book of #1 Hits'', 5th Edition (Billboard Publications), page 157.</ref> It was also Orbison's third single to top the [[UK Singles Chart]] (for a total of three weeks).<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book| first= David| last= Roberts| year= 2006| title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]| edition= 19th| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited | location= London| isbn= 1-904994-10-5| page= 186}}</ref> The record ultimately sold seven million copies and marked the high point in Orbison's career.<ref>Lehman, Peter. ''Roy Orbison: Invention of an Alternative Rock Masculinity''. Philadelphia: Temple UP, 2003, p. 2, 13</ref> Within months of its release, in October 1964, the single was certified [[gold record|gold]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]].<ref>{{cite certification|region=United States|title=Pretty Woman|artist=Roy Orbison}}</ref> At the year's end, ''Billboard'' ranked it the number four song of 1964.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=January 2, 1965|title=Hot 100 Singles of 1964|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/60s/1965/Billboard%201965-01-02.pdf|journal=Billboard|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> \"Oh, Pretty Woman\" was eventually the basis for the 1990 film ''[[Pretty Woman]]'' starring [[Richard Gere]] and [[Julia Roberts]], and the 2018 Broadway musical ''[[Pretty Woman: The Musical]]''.\n\n==Overview==\nThe lyrics tell the story of a man who sees a pretty woman walking by. He yearns for her and wonders if, as beautiful as she is, she might be lonely like he is. At the last minute, she turns back and joins him. The title was inspired by Orbison's wife, Claudette, interrupting a conversation to announce she was going out. When Orbison asked if she had enough cash, his co-writer Bill Dees interjected, \"[[Roy Orbison#Riding the success|A pretty woman never needs any money]].\"<ref>Amburn, Ellis. ''Dark Star: The Roy Orbison Story''. New York: Carol Publishing, 1990, p. 127</ref>\n\nOrbison's recording of the song was produced by [[Fred Foster]]<ref name=\"500 Number One Hits\" /> on 1 August 1964. There were four guitar players on the session: Roy Orbison, Billy Sanford, [[Jerry Kennedy]], and [[Wayne Moss]].<ref name=SessionReport>{{citation |date=7 September 1964 |title=Phonograph Recording Contract, Local Union No. 257 |publisher=American Federation of Musicians of the United States and Canada |publication-place=Fred Foster Sound Studios, Nashville, TN}}</ref> Sanford, who later played on sessions for [[Elvis Presley]], [[Don Williams]] and many others, played the intro guitar.  Williams introduced him as a kid who had just arrived in Nashville, with a borrowed guitar, who heard Orbison was minus a guitar player, went over and got the gig. Other musicians on the record included [[Floyd Cramer]] on piano, [[Henry Strzelecki]] on upright bass, [[Boots Randolph]] and [[Charlie McCoy]] on saxophones, [[Buddy Harman]] on drums, and Paul Garrison on percussion.<ref name=SessionReport /> Orbison played a 12-string [[Epiphone]]. [[Bill Porter (sound engineer)|Bill Porter]] served as recording engineer for the song.<ref>{{Cite AV media notes |title= The Monument Story|title-link= |others= Various|year= |chapter= |url= |access-date= |first= |last= |author-link= |first2= |last2= |author-link2= |page= |pages= |type= |publisher= Sony Music Entertainment|id= A2K66106|location= New York, New York|ref=}}</ref>\n\nOrbison posthumously won the 1991 [[Grammy Award for Best Male Pop Vocal Performance]] for his live recording of \"Oh Pretty Woman\" on his [[HBO]] television special ''[[Roy Orbison and Friends, A Black and White Night]]''. In 1999, the song was honored with a [[Grammy Hall of Fame Award]] and was named one of the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]'s [[The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame's 500 Songs that Shaped Rock and Roll|500 Songs that Shaped Rock and Roll]]. In 2004, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine ranked it #224 on their list of the \"[[500 Greatest Songs of All Time]].\" On May 14, 2008, The [[Library of Congress]] selected the song for preservation in the [[National Recording Registry]].\n\n===Lawsuit against 2 Live Crew===\n{{Further|Campbell v. Acuff-Rose Music, Inc.}}\nIn 1989, rap group [[2 Live Crew]] recorded a [[parody]] of the Orbison song, using the alternate title \"Pretty Woman\", for their album ''[[As Nasty As They Wanna Be#As Clean As They Wanna Be|As Clean As They Wanna Be]]''. 2 Live Crew [[sampling (music)|sample]]d the distinctive [[bassline]] from the Orbison song, but replaced the original lyrics with talk about a hairy woman and her bald-headed friend and their appeal to the singer, as well as denunciation of a \"two-timing woman.\"\n\nOrbison's publisher, [[Acuff-Rose Music]] sued 2 Live Crew on the basis that the [[fair use]] doctrine did not permit reuse of their [[copyright]]ed material for profit. The case, ''[[Campbell v. Acuff-Rose Music, Inc.]]'' went all the way to the [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]]. The Supreme Court decided in 2 Live Crew's favor, greatly expanding the doctrine of fair use and extending its protections to parodies created for profit. It is considered a seminal fair use decision.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Jackson|first1=Matt|title=Commerce versus art: The transformation of fair use|journal=Journal of Broadcasting & Electronic Media|date=March 1995|volume=39|issue=2|pages=190\u2013199|doi=10.1080/08838159509364298}}</ref>\n\n==Chart history==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Chart (1964\u201365)\n! scope=\"col\" | Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite book | title=[[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book (1940\u20131969)]] | author=Kent, David | authorlink=David Kent (historian) | publisher=Australian Chart Book | location=[[Turramurra]] | year=2005 | isbn=0-646-44439-5}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|Austria|5|artist=Roy Orbison|song=Oh, Pretty Woman|accessdate=August 21, 2014}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|Flanders|1|artist=Roy Orbison|song=Oh, Pretty Woman|accessdate=August 21, 2014}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Belgium ([[Ultratop|Ultratop 40]] Wallonia)<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=OSAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA19#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Hits of the World | journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | issue=50 | page=19 | volume=76 | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | date=December 12, 1964 | issn=0006-2510}}</ref>\n| 5\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Canada ([[RPM (magazine)|''RPM'']])<ref name=\"CAN-sin\">{{cite web | url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.4702&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=bb0e7somh8osmahbvuk8ubb1u5 | title=Top Singles \u2013 Volume 2, No. 5, September 28 1964 | publisher=[[Walt Grealis]] | work=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]] | accessdate=August 22, 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313204743/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.4702&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=bb0e7somh8osmahbvuk8ubb1u5 | archive-date=March 13, 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Denmark ([[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry|IFPI]])<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=biAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA15#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Hits of the World | journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | issue=49 | page=15 | volume=76 | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | date=December 5, 1964 | issn=0006-2510}}</ref>\n| 3\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | France ([[Institut fran\u00e7ais d'opinion publique|IFOP]])<ref name=\"FRA-sin\">{{cite web | url=http://www.infodisc.fr/Bilan_O.php | title=Acc\u00e8s direct \u00e0 ces Artistes: Roy Orbison | publisher=InfoDisc | accessdate=August 21, 2014 | language=French | format=select \"Roy ORBISON\" and then click \"Go\" | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140924114622/http://www.infodisc.fr/Bilan_O.php | archivedate=September 24, 2014 }}</ref>\n| 8\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Finland ([[The Official Finnish Charts|Suomen virallinen lista]])<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KEUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA19#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Hits of the World | journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | issue=1 | page=19 | volume=77 | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | date=January 2, 1965 | issn=0006-2510}}</ref>\n| 9\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ireland ([[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA]])<ref name=\"IRL-sin\">{{cite web | url=http://irishcharts.ie/search/placement | title=Search the Charts | publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]] | work=irishcharts.ie | accessdate=August 22, 2014 | format=enter \"Roy Orbison\" into the \"Search by Artist\" box, then select \"Search\" | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721125210/http://irishcharts.ie/search/placement | archive-date=July 21, 2011 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|Dutch40|3|artist=Roy Orbison|song=Pretty Woman|week=1|year=1965|accessdate=August 21, 2014}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|Dutch100|1|artist=Roy Orbison|song=Oh, Pretty Woman|accessdate=August 21, 2014}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|Norway|1|artist=Roy Orbison|song=Oh, Pretty Woman|accessdate=August 21, 2014}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | New Zealand (Lever Hit Parade)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=Lever+hit+parades&qyear=1964&qmonth=Oct&qweek=22-Oct-1964#n_view_location|title=flavour of new zealand - Lever hit parades|author=|date=|website=www.flavourofnz.co.nz|accessdate=April 10, 2018}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Switzerland ([[Swiss Hitparade|Schweizer Hitparade]])<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=mCgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA24#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Hits of the World | journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | issue=8 | page=24 | volume=77 | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | date=February 20, 1965 | issn=0006-2510}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|UK|1|artist=Roy Orbison|song=Oh Pretty Woman|date=1964-10-10|accessdate=August 21, 2014}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|Billboardhot100|1|artist=Roy Orbison|song=Oh, Pretty Woman|artistid={{BillboardID|Roy Orbison}} | accessdate=August 21, 